text:
#somethingforeveryone made by community for community, on www.rainieravenueradio.world. listen online or on the tunein app.

friday nov 23rd

10:30am @seamonsterradio 
ep 10 - celebrating women of the sea monster lounge. every song played this week will feature women with a connection to the sea monster lounge. we also interview karen "kz" zamm, kate olson and michelle searle, discussing how they help the community, the topic of the #metoo movement and how it's affecting seattle, and more. artists played include champagne honeybee, clarkia cobb, liberty strikes, marina christopher, syrinx effect and more surprises.

11:30am #singlefather project by @jalalwilson1
ep 38 - teaching children to overcome obstacles and overcoming obstacles as parents.

noon #fitness corner with mark bryant @worldchamp2000
ep 24 - big-t taurus niumata talked about his first powerlifting world championship.

12:30pm #seniors matter with brenda charles-edwards ep 63 - live 11/23/18 12:30pm.

1pm seattle here & now by john yasutake 
ep 62 - officer jim ritter, the lgbtq liaison of the seattle police department talks about his role with the department in serving this population.

2pm #communityspotlight 
ep 44 - the @seattlepubliclibrary chief librarian, marcellus turner interviewed by yvette dinish.

2:30pm you can make a difference with mac macgregor @thegendersensei
ep 32 - jalair box, one of the founders of speak out seattle, prioritizes public safety, focuses on what works to solve homelessness, and supports substance abuse prevention and treatment.

3pm the other side with rev robert jeffrey 
ep 28 - rabbi david basior of kadima reconstructionist community reflects on the pittsburgh synogogue shooting and the killings of 2 african americans in kentucky.

3:30pm mondo's world 
ep 43 - program manager for outdoors for all foundation, alex jones, shares how his organization assists disabled veterans and people in wheelchairs to mountain bike, cycle, ski, kayak, and more.

4pm #trafficjam

text:
you've all posted engagement/wedding/pregnancy announcements/updates and/or baby pics, well, life works in different ways for others! .
i have been travelling for a few years and am currently in peru continuing my education but my anxiety and ptsd issues that decided to return a few years ago? yeah, they came back with a vengance. i've done the work- drugs, medications - hated both but worked as temporary band-aid solutions- , hours of therapy as well to develop a toolbox of tricks for when issues arise- but there was nothing left this time. i needed help, got help, and the resulting consensus was for an emotional therapy support animal. .
so,  my 5 year old fur-baby named pelusa (long hair/fluffy in spanish) decided to adopt me and yes, there will be many more photos of her to come!! 48 hours into our forever relationship, we're adjusting well ğŸ˜â¤ï¸ we've made it to school and discovered the joys of the park nearby and yes, she totally snuggles up at night for bedtime bellyrubs. she doesn't know what to do with her pink bear because i don't think she's ever had a toy before but she was so tired she passed right out! and she's started using her bowls (instead of insisting on eating out of my hand) .
.
.
.

text:
dear best friend, "meeting you was fate but being with you was my best choice"

neither did you expressed your love nor you have said that. but in your fights, taunts and scolds you made me realize that more adorable than it would have been expressed. because self-realization is beautiful in its own way. 
from laughing at my lame jokes to controlling laughter at my super jokes from a stranger you became my amigo. making my sad tears fall down the cheeks as happy tears you cared me like a sibling in their absence. 
giving an ear to my blunders and never-ending  talks to a hand on my shoulder with words "it's ok!" you easily handled my weird moods. you simply amazed me by switching to different roles within a span of seconds.  astonishing me with words of motivation during the period of difficulties to being a constant supporter in front of the world you have never left a stone to awe me. no matter what i did, you never judged me instead corrected me.  no matter how bad and stupid i'm, you loved me unconditionally. while people laughed at the stains of blood behind my dress you respected the womanhood in me. 
while you been stern and rigid, at an instance, i felt too, kick you up. yet! only to realize later you were pulling me from stepping on pricks of hardships and hurdles. you loved me as a sister and respected me as a girl.

while i was enjoying the most beautiful journey of life you entered and made the life more dramatic. while others paved a way out of my life in worst days you shined and glowed like a diya of clout and courage. you came to my life and scorched the demons in me and of my life. moreover, you gave me another family, you been my prodigy and the best treasure of life.
.
.
swetha prabhu.
(@swethagprabhu)
.
.

text:
once upon a time you had it all sorted out, and then you didn't. as we talk to our church family, many are in the wandering. looking for a new church home. i know the anguish, anxiety,  and heartache this poses for many. we were there too. but i pray you follow the holy spirit and seek your next steps.
god will guide you and bring you new friends, dreams, passions,  and desires. you will make a difference, and will be appreciated for your giftings.
the word will come alive....again, and you will find the fire in your soul to help others. it will take some time to heal. but you will be able to help others while you heal. wounded healers. 
in anything you recover from, it's more about what you say yes to. "may you be an explorer, may you recover delight and wonder and curiosity and your faith about god, and about the story with which you continue to wrestle." sarah bessey-out of sorts
we love you. and we love our new church home, family life community church.  #churchfamily #littlefamily #familylife #hopegiver #mommyhood  #makeadifference #outofsorts #propelwomen #lifeischoice #voicetothevoiceless

text:
a group of women and girls, all of whom are related, in the city of villa fiorito. 
despite a 2012 law which raised the maximum prison sentence for â€œfemicide,â€ the killing of a woman or girl on account of her gender, argentina is still struggling against widespread gender-based violence. thankfully, a grassroots, women-led movement known as ni una menos (not one [woman] less) has arisen in argentina, and is working to empower women and defend their human rights. in this series, karl mancini (@karlitomancini) shares some of his work on the inspiring women of ni una menos and their fight for justice. to learn more about both mancini's work and ni una menos, please follow the link in our bio.

text:
#justbecause

#justbecause i happen to look at you doesn't mean i am interested in you.

#justbecause i smile and talk doesn't mean i am easy to approach.

#justbecause i don't raise my voice to create a hue and cry doesn't mean 'something' went unnoticed.

#justbecause i wear  traditional doesn't mean i have to be addressed with 'respect' publically and attempted personally.

#justbecause

this post is not another #metoo movement or any gender-specific voice. it is about day-to-day living, dealing people and daily interactions. 
it's weird how people draw conclusions without even knowing you and it's worse when they create an uncomfortable environment for you #justbecause you choose to take a stand not by making noise but by changing responses. 
if only it was easier to live and let live safely!

if safety was just about being physically safe, we would all hire body guards as we hire helpers for our daily odds.

safety has a lot to do with the mind and heart.  and sadly, we can only guard our own mind and heart to feel mentally and emotionally safe.

#justbecause  it's your mind, so only you can fix it.

#justbecause

text:
a group of women and girls, all of whom are related, in the city of villa fiorito. 
despite a 2012 law which raised the maximum prison sentence for â€œfemicide,â€ the killing of a woman or girl on account of her gender, argentina is still struggling against widespread gender-based violence. thankfully, a grassroots, women-led movement known as ni una menos (not one [woman] less) has arisen in argentina, and is working to empower women and defend their human rights. in this series, karl mancini (@karlitomancini) shares some of his work on the inspiring women of ni una menos and their fight for justice. to learn more about both mancini's work and ni una menos, please follow the link in our bio. 
#opensociety #argentina #niunamenos #femicide #femicidio #conmisderechosnotemetas #16days #genderbasedviolence #metoo #hearmetoo

text:
victim shaming is the most convenient thing the society does whenever an assault or harassment takes place. there is a lack of gender sensitisation in the institutions meant for quality education and imbibing equality. restricting women in the name of security instills only fear in their minds and the perpetrators try to find an easy path to get away with it. broaden your perspective, maybe then you will be able to understand the issues which don't concern you in particular but matter to the society in general.
-kshitij

addressing the womenâ€™s right to be heard in all manners of life. i was inspired by an article from @thecut during the #kavanaughhearings.

text:
there is no sexual harassment without sexual corruption (mental corruption). what has a 3months old or 70years old grandmother done to warrant rape?

the violence against personsâ€™ prohibition act (vappa) accords the national agency for the prohibition of trafficking in persons (naptip) the responsibility of operationalising and implementing the vapp act 2015. the vapp act couldn't see the light of the day until after 14years of hardwork to have the bill passed. as a law passed by the national assembly, the juridical scope of operation of the vappa is limited to the fct. state houses of assembly will need to pass the law to suit their governance context before it is operational at the state level. 
the challenge however is that the scope of the problem of sexual violence and violation transcends the fct. it is an issue of utmost public interest and concern across nigeria and globally as evidenced by the presence of sexual referral centres in states such as kaduna, lagos and ekiti and the #metoo movement. it can equally be inferred in the national outrage that followed the recent tragic case of the 13 year old ochanya ogbanje who died following years of sexual abuse within the family. 
there is a need to create a national register which exposes perpetrators of any form of abuse to reduce the increasing rates of violence in our society. we need to name and shame them.

at this point, everyone should be part of this amazing work. support the cause!  #endgbv #womennotobjects #warif

text:
oh the tears i have shed.
i donâ€™t think i knew what weeping was until i looked at my daughter and thought about how iâ€™ve treated myself all these years. from addictive and compulsive behaviors started by my body dysmorphia to sexual abuse to obsessive weight control issues to the depths of a nearly successful suicide attempt... i weep because during my whole life i have loved almost everyone and everything but myself. iâ€™ve abused and been abused and my life experience as a whole has been a really tough pill to swallow. i spend a lot of... well i used to spend a lot of time hating myself. stuck on these repeat records of hate speech.
â€œyouâ€™re a loserâ€ â€œyouâ€™re fatâ€ â€œyouâ€™re damagedâ€ â€œno ones going to want youâ€ â€œyouâ€™re never going to accomplish anythingâ€ â€œyou should dieâ€ â€œeveryone else would be better off if you were goneâ€
what would i do if i heard my daughter say that to herself? will i be able to tell her sheâ€™s beautiful like my mom tried to tell me? will i be able to brush the hair out of her face and make her believe in herself when the first boy she loves breaks her heart or god forbid sexually abuse her like i have been?
i will be able to help my daughter ... if i can start doing that to myself and stay true to the course. all this time i just needed to start forgiving that girl that made those decisions for the better part of twenty years.... twenty years. now i get to be the women i never would have listened to. thatâ€™s how iâ€™ll help ari. thatâ€™s how iâ€™ll help myself. iâ€™m only so candid because i know that there just has to be other people out there like me. i also know that i will be judged for being honest and iâ€™m cool with that too - itâ€™s just a weeding out process. donâ€™t fear the process. donâ€™t suffer. find your tribe. you donâ€™t have to shout it from the rooftops but donâ€™t withdraw into yourself... a sick mind is too dangerous a neighborhood to walk alone in.. reach out â™¥ï¸ and have a beautiful weekend people.

text:

text:
there is a stress gap between men and women
________
studies show that women are twice as likely to suffer from anxiety and sever stress (surprise!) - we experience more insomnia, and even when we do get a full night of sleep, it is usually filled with problem-solving dreams. so we wake up as tired as we were the night before. 
________
in many cases (but not all), women do more (sometimes x3) of unpaid domestic work, than men. i highly encourage our well-working system : i cooked, you clean lol 
also - stop assuming that domestic chores are not work. every little bit is!
________
female managers (and others) are more likely to display â€œsurface acting,â€ - or forcing emotions that are not felt (tell me about it...) surface acting is a form of emotional labor. yup. 
itâ€™s not easy to pretend like youâ€™re not surrounded by idiots. 
my advice:
we all should just go on the emotional labor strike.

text:
i google your name at 11:02 p.m. cause all i want now is to see a recent photograph of you. one you took within the last week.

yesterday i wanted to know if you are okay. i refreshed your blog but there was nothing new. no new sad poem.

day before yesterday i stared at your phone number for half an hour at 09:02 a.m. but i couldn't think of anything to say to you.

a day before that i couldn't stop myself from opening that folder in my laptop i have saved as your nickname. i read our old conversations. i listened to your voice notes and i cried over the same things once again.

a day before that i wrote a poem about you and i smiled when i read it cause it looked like you.

a day before that i thought all day about the things i would ask you if i ever talked to you and i counted 26 questions that wouldn't offend you. 
a day before that nothing mattered to me. not you. not me. not my feelings or your feelings. i was sure my heart had turned into stone.

it's 05:04 a.m. now and a new day. i am still thinking about you and i just want to know what was the last thing that made you laugh. /sahiba

text:
la giornata internazionale contro la violenza sulle donne, istituita dallâ€™assemblea delle nazioni unite nel 1999, invita tutti noi a riflettere su un problema enorme, purtroppo ancora lontano da una soluzione. 
la violenza contro le donne si manifesta in vari modi: violenza fisica, violenza sessuale, lo stupro e la violenza psicologica. spesso a compiere queste violenze sono i partner o gli ex-partner che talvolta spingono le situazioni allâ€™estremo con i casi di femminicidio. 
noi di fucina n.4 vogliamo cogliere lâ€™invito alla riflessione sul tema analizzandolo da un punto di vista differente: quello degli uomini maltrattanti. per fare questo abbiamo invitato per il 26 novembre a motta di livenza lâ€™associazione pordenonese in prima persona - uomini contro la violenza sulle donne. questa associazione, fondata nel novembre del 2016, riunisce una trentina di iscritti di diversa provenienza professionale ed etÃ . tra i principali obiettivi ci sono la costituzione di un centro di ascolto per uomini maltrattanti e degli incontri di sensibilizzazione con le scuole. interverranno due soci fondatori del gruppo, antonio aprea e lo psichiatra carlo rizzo, che affronteranno il problema della violenza maschile e del "maltrattante della porta accanto". insieme a loro saranno presenti lâ€™attrice bianca manzari con la quale approfondiremo alcune letture e pablo perissinotto cantautore che da qualche tempo collabora con lâ€™associazione.

in prima persona: parole e musica contro la violenza sulle donne
lunedÃ¬ 26 novembre, ore 20.45
sala della loggia, motta di livenza (tv)
interverranno:
* antonio aprea, socio fondatore di in prima persona * carlo rizzo, psichiatra * bianca manzari, attrice * pablo perissinotto, cantautore

noi di fucina n.4 vogliamo cogliere lâ€™invito alla riflessione sul tema analizzandolo da un punto di vista differente: quello degli uomini maltrattanti. per fare questo abbiamo invitato per il 26 novembre a motta di livenza lâ€™associazione pordenonese in prima persona - uomini contro la violenza sulle donne. questa associazione, fondata nel novembre del 2016, riunisce una trentina di iscritti di diversa provenienza professionale ed etÃ . tra i principali obiettivi ci sono la costituzione di un centro di ascolto per uomini maltrattanti e degli incontri di sensibilizzazione con le scuole. interverranno due soci fondatori del gruppo, antonio aprea e lo psichiatra carlo rizzo, che affronteranno il problema della violenza maschile e del "maltrattante della poa accan noto". insieme a loro saranno presenti lâ€™attrice bianca manzari con la quale approfondiremo alcune letture e pablo perissinotto can notautore che da qualche tempo collabora con lâ€™associazione.

text:
seven years ago, iran's bill for the protection of women against violence made it to parliament. seven years later, it's being reviewed by religious leaders while women and girls across the country--especially those with disabilities--remain vulnerable to various forms of violence with no legal protections. in a statement issued ahead of the international day for the elimination of violence against women, the center for human rights in iran calls upon the iranian authorities to engage civil society, listen to women's rights activist and prioritize and pass this legislation before more innocent women and girls are endangered due to the lack of legal protections in iran. read our in-depth report about this important issue on our website.â €
â €

text:
the #metoo movement is a movement against sexual harassment and assault that has created a sea change for victims of it. now more than ever before, women are speaking up about their experiences, and perpetrators are being called upon to account for their actions. given the global nature of sexual harassment, sexual assault, and violence against women, it asks what responsibilities we have as a youth. 
let us seize this moment of opportunity marking 16 days of violence against gender based violence to create an
inclusive and diverse environment conducive to share our stories of understanding.

speak up. make your voice matter.

reach out your #metoo story. bit.ly/mymetoostory

text:
dear 5th semester,
it's been a rollercoaster ride for me . met many lovely people , lost too . overwhelmed by all the human emotions - love, care, heartbreak, betrayal, compassion, innocence, nuisance...etc etc
but yeah it's was quite an experience. i wish another semesters goes like this . glad to meet new people, different from me in all aspects but can't ask for more. sorry to people with whom i couldn't spend time especially @tej_naren babe me olives youâ¤ . did so much of bakchodi , bunked classes for doing projects and assignments ( which we didn't do :p) . got screwed by teachers but who cares , we made memories . misunderstood each other but still cared for each other . 
in the beginning of this semester i never thought it will be so great , wow it was amazing . i wish we be the same untill the end of this 4 year of torturing engineering life and even after that . 
i might irritate , screw , curse , fight with you guys but from bottom of my heart love you guys alot. (ps : hate you more â¤) thank you fam
yours pshyco bro -_-

text_retweet:
taking over open society foundationsâ€™s instagram for a week with photos from my long term project 'ni una menos' on gender violence and women's movements fight for rights. 
glad to have the opportunity to give visibility on this important and current issue in the week of november 25th, the international day for the elimination of violence against women.
more info about 'ni una menos' on the website dedicated to the project www.niunamenosproject.com

#repost @opensocietyfoundations
(@get_repost)
â€¢ â€¢ â€¢
a woman and her three daughters. after dozens of appeals to the police went unanswered, this woman separated from her abusive ex-husband. still, she cannot count on local law enforcement to protect her rights. 
despite a 2012 law which raised the maximum prison sentence for â€œfemicide,â€ the killing of a woman or girl on account of her gender, argentina is still struggling against widespread gender-based violence. thankfully, a grassroots, women-led movement known as ni una menos (not one [woman] less) has arisen in argentina, and is working to empower women and defend their human rights. in this series, karl mancini (@karlitomancini) shares some of his work on the inspiring women of ni una menos and their fight for justice. to learn more about both mancini's work and ni una menos, please follow the link in our bio.

text:
november 25th is iinternational day  for the elimination of violence against women.
.
.
over the years, survivors and activists, through various campaigns such as #metoo, #timesup, #notonemore, have reached its peak. violence against women and girls cannot be and shouldn't be silenced. women and girls all over the world  are experiencing  abuse in various ways. .
.
the impact of violence is quite significant for these women and girls. women abused by their intimate partner, are 16% likely to have a low-birth-weight baby, likely to experience depression and 1.5 times likely to acquire hiv and sti.
physical, emotional and financial toll of violence sets women back from reaching their maximum potential.
.
.

text:
daphne is a free spirited girl who lives with her bohemian family in london, which consists of her writer father ed, an activist mother ellie and a scholarly brother theo. ed and ellie, who are too busy in their pursuits and â€œaffairsâ€, do not believe in conventional parenting and want their children to find their own way in life. daphne also has a best friend jane, who is smart and mature, but at the same time desires to be what daphne is, an object of everyoneâ€™s desire. enter ralph, a musician with an inherent charm and devil may care attitude. sparks fly between daphne and ralph, and each is convinced that he/she is in love. only issue; daphne is nine and ralph is twenty-seven.

the book explores the issue of pedophilia, but not in a very didactic or pontificating tone. at no point in the narrative did i feel that the situation was such that there was a moral absolute and therefore definitely a victim party to side with. this is because the power of @sofkazinovieff writing is such that it actually almost humanized ralphâ€™s character at times. it explored the mind of a pedophile very well; to him love was an emotion beyond the constraints of age and sex was just an act of expressing love. daphne was convinced of the same, till years later she saw the situation in a different light, when she was herself the mother of a daughter. janeâ€™s motive for pushing daphne towards seeking justice was kept a well-guarded secret till the very end; which at many times would make the readerâ€™s question her intentions. it also made me wonder if it is the situations and surroundings that contribute to such behavior. ed and ellie gave their children freedom, but wasnâ€™t it also necessary for them to give them guidance and the safety net of a home. was it the â€œhippie rock-n-rollâ€ culture of the seventies that just normalized this behavior?

in the end i wanted justice to be served; and this is where many readers would have been left frustrated. but may be there was catharsis to be found? comparisons of this book to lolita are inevitable; but it comes in a very different era and at a time when the fires of #metoo are blazing across the globe. it is a #mustread of 2018.
#putney

text:
this #16daysofactivism remember to check in on your sisters. remember to hold them close, embrace them, remind them that they are valuable. that they are worthy of joy, laughter and light. 
every day is about fighting the ugliness with love and stretching out our hands, opening our hearts to hear the stories of others and helping them heal. 
i feel very strongly about sensationalising stories of abuse and violence, prioritising these stories and merely hashtaging #metoo without taking some time out to really create spaces where victims of abuse can be angry, sad, frustrated confused, and then talk until they come out of that darkness. it isn't enough to make these stories trend. we also need to make sure they never happen again, we can only do this through the power of sisterhood which always affirms our purpose beyond and away from situations and people that hurt us.

text:
(tw // assault & rape) #thisisnotconsent 
it's 2018. the #metoo movement is strong. women all over the world, including myself, are speaking out about their experiences with sexual assault and rape after being silenced for years. finally, finally, we feel as if we are getting somewhere. we are finally getting it through to men that they do not have a right to our bodie and our bodies will be forever ours and only ours to do what we like with.

and then, a 17 year old girl is blamed for her rape - because she was wearing the "wrong type of underwear". her lace fronted thong clearly meant she was asking for it. it is 2018, and our society is still trying to come up with ways to justify rape and sexual assault. it is 2018, and we are teaching young women to be scared to go out in even jeans and a t-shirt because they will be catcalled and wolf-whistled, being made into prey for other people to stare at. it is 2018, and we are bringing young women up being taught how not to be raped, rather than bringing our young men up being taught not to rape. it is 2018, and young women still cannot even wear pretty underwear just for ourselves without being told we are just doing it for attention. it is 2018, and we are still asking for it. it is still our fault.

i wasn't asking for it. my friends who have spoken up were not asking for it. that young, strong, gorgeous 17 year old was not asking for it. none of us were asking for it to happen to us - when will you stop trying to convince the world that we were? how many more beautiful young girls need to go through this and the subsequent embarrassment, mental and physical trauma and humiliation before you realise that our clear, resounding no, means no?

our clothing has never and will never equal our consent.

#metoo  #metooindia ,pic of today 23/ 11/ 2018
look at the pic,51c madhuban enclave main rohtak road new delhi -63
have been doing illegal unauthorised construction openly but mcd,dda,delhi police have been taking action against them.all antisocials of h.no.51c,veena saluja,guddu thekedar & others have been doing ilegal construction for the last 2 months but responsible authorities have been sleeping.now antisocials have been breaking dda wall without permission but no authority posted penalty on them nor police arrested them till today.is it democracy in india?is this corruption is motive of bjp party?is it not protection and support to antisocials by mcd,dda,delhi police? are bjp party and other authorities not responsible for this unauthorised construction in dda flats? who will punish those ,who have not been doing their duty honestly?

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
"if married, we're called aunty.
if single, it's lame.
if unmarried it's shame...shame.
to quote shakespeare:
"what's in a name?"
why do you play this game of surnames?
if i study a lot,then....."hey nerd"
if i use too much lipstick,then..."hey heroine"
if i reach home late,you doubt my character.
all i want to say,
"where the hell are my rights?"
whether it's size zero or xxl,
it's our lives, so what the hell
let go of the taunts,
that's what women want.
to be,to live,to love...
stay quite or just flaunt!! " -kareena kapoor khan

kareena kapoor khan made a poetic pitch for women's rights at the launch of her maiden radio show:what women want.
the actress discuss women issues with celebrities and non-celebrities.on the #ishqfm show that will air from december 2018.she also praised #metoo movement.

her full speech is given below! "it shouldn't be allowed to die down.the fact that so many women have come out and spoken.i think that's a start.the fact is that earlier people have not spoken for years.today people have come out and i really really appreciate those women,who actually had the courage to stand up and talk.and that is going to help all of us change our workplace,give us security.and whoever it is,big or small,there's no place.it has to be safe.and the most important thing is that we have to keep this,we have to keep momentum going,we have to keep the conversation alive.and once we keep that alive, a lot will change,it's here today,this moment,this season...be unapologetically sexy,be unapologetically awesome"

text:
the man in image 1 is a maintenance boy alleged to have masterbated in a lift in front of a 2nd year student of srm university, kattankulatur, chennai when this gross behaviour was informed to the administration, they turned a blind eye and gave reluctant response to the victim. they blamed her being a girl from north india studying in south which led her face this. they also threatened that they know about girls doing alcohol and cigarettes in hostels. this sort of discrimination and orthodox attitude makes the administration an acquaintance in the crime as well. what followed were series of protests not very commonly seen in private universities. 
as of now, the maintenance boy has not been traced after the incident. as the administration is answerable and accountable to the deeds of the man and those who took the incident lightly,  one question must pertain, "are women really safe in campuses albeit the restrictions imposed on them ?" @pinjratod 
#srmuniversity #metoo #molestationawareness #protest #chennai.
.

text:
despite the fact that ethlyne clair (born november 23, 1904) was probably one of the most beautiful women ever to grace the screen during the late 1920s/early 1930s, she never became a star.
â€¢
ethlyne made her break for stardom after winning a beauty contest in her home town of talladega, alabama, and headed to new york to find work as an extra (her first role of note was in sandra (1924) starring barbara la marr). â€¢
â€¢
in hollywood, she signed a contract with universal; appearing in a handful of comedies shorts, including the newlyweds, followed by a spate of westerns opposite hoot gibson. â€¢
â€¢
in 1928, she married her agent, richard lonsdale hinshaw, in mexico. it was an unhappy union; she later revealed he forced her into marriage at gunpoint. her career also waned, after playing second fiddle to rex, the wonder horse, she left universal, and freelanced. it was pathÃ©, representing a variety of independent film studios, who nominated her as one of the years wampas baby stars of 1929. the accolade kept her in the press; she was also one of hollywoodâ€™s first stars to launch her own beauty care range. it was this which brought her to the attention of ernest westmore, of the hollywood make-up dynasty.
â€¢
divorced from her husband, her marriage to ernest wasnâ€™t without drama; when at their wedding, his first wife showed up with their daughter, muriel, dressed in rags to highlight the state of poverty ernest had left them in. ernest in turn flew at photographers; got into a brawl and was arrested. as his career flourished, ethlyneâ€™s went into a deep decline; her temporary contract with warner bros. had expired and she was out of work. later, in 1991, she claimed that mogul daryl zanuck ruined her career after she refused his sexual advances. â€¢
â€¢
by 1934, with her film career over, she tried her hand on the stage with limited results. instead, divorced from ernest, she married again, to a second-hand car salesman, and retired to raise her family. she died in february 1996, aged 91.
â€¢
â€¢

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
there is an exciting movement happening at present where conversations, previously shunned, are being welcomed and celebrated. men and women are finding themselves - women discovering a strength that they had historically suppressed and men a vulnerability - due to unwritten societal rules
.
whilst this movement is revolutionary, it is bringing with it a sense of unease and uncertainty experienced more so by men. historically men have been depicted as pillars of strength, power, leadership and as providers in society. thankfully in the millennial era we understand that there is nothing tougher or more resilient than being vulnerable
.
life affects us all, financial worries, relationship breakdowns, grief, stress, joy, babies, marriage, affairs etc etc happen to men and women and there is no right or wrong way to respond. we all have the same emotional needs and we must all work to create a society where everyone can open up and feel how they want to feel without judgement
.
with the highest rate of suicide, mental health problems and illicit drug and alcohol abuse, men are struggling to cope. the stats are shocking and it is the duty of all to show encouragement and support for men to be true to themselves
.
november is an important month because it raises awareness of issues affecting men specifically, but we must all be mindful and extend our gratitude, celebration and protection of men and their wellbeing always.
.
some key messages for men especially:
itâ€™s ok to not be ok but itâ€™s not ok to not get help for it. donâ€™t suffer in silence.
.
more men than you would ever imagine are going through the same stressors, opening up will let them open up too. connection is key.
.
worrying signs : sad all the time, tired all the time, not sleeping, over-sleeping, loss of appetite, unable to enjoy things previously loved, reduced libido, feelings of hopelessness, suicide, self harm - any of these, go see your gp asap. .
wellness is gender-neutral. our health is our single most valuable asset, we must protect it and help others understand the value of their wellbeing too. .
#menshealth #yourlifestyledoctors #healthawareness #mentalhealth #wellbeing #wellness #health #life

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
milkman is a flipping masterpiece.  it's such a magnificent read (clever, funny, haunting, devastating) and so timely given today's discussions on both the precariousness of the good friday agreement and male sexual entitlement (two of the main themes of this book.) on a personal level, while not anywhere near as serious as ni, i grew up in a small scottish town rife with sectarian divisions. this book articulates so many experiences i've had and never been able to articulate properly. 
but if you've no knowledge of that area 
this is a timeless book that would appeal to anyone who's felt limited by the weight of place, culture and gossip. 
a totally worthy winner of the @manbookerprize2018 #milkman #annaburns #manbookerprize #metoo

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
anxiety can impact physical and mental health. there are short- and long-term effects on both the mind and body.
while many people know about the effects of anxiety on mental health, fewer people are aware of the physical side effects, which can include digestive issues and an increased risk of infection. anxiety can also change the function of the cardiovascular, urinary, and respiratory systems.

in this article, we discuss the most common physical symptoms and side effects of anxiety. https://youwillbearwitness.com/2018/11/22/the-effects-of-anxiety-on-the-body/ #youwillbearwitness #ptsdawareness #ptsd #doitfordolly #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #metoo #trauma #cardinalpell #dissociativeidentitydisorder

text:
(3/3)
as someone who travels alone extensively, iran was rough to navigate as a woman alone, not in a tour group, not with a male partner or companion, not being taxied about from one perfect sight directly to another perfect site and staying by the picturesque reflection pool of a beautifully maintained guest house half the day. a lot of the time, out on the streets and in the less touristy bazaars and sitting in popular parks, there were iranian women and men of all ages who were openly hostile toward a young woman alone. it was incredibly hard and doing workaway toward the end of my month in iran was what saved me.

my experience had been turned around nearly 180 degrees and i met the most amazing iranians and fellow travellers who all changed not just my trip but my life.

it has take me a long time to be able to sit with my trauma and i'm now ready to speak about my experiences and the beautiful people i met, not without also acknowledging the really difficult times.

1: hajar @cafelingo.iran founder & owner
2: haghighi family, martin and david
@sueiranpour @proshathaghighi
3: shirin @shirin.ziai
4: students who came to @cafelingo.iran (please tag yourselves if you see this!) @mehrbod18
5: clemence @crxla
6: martin & mogli @motomogli

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this is an original i was recording or more precisely had to write and record although i was having swollen vocal chords. what was such an urgency you ask? then the answer is myental space. i had to put out the chaos by any means.
i am the person who believes that diseases are simply energy defficiency and disorders. specifically i believed that mental disorders arent actually treated by medication rather one has to heal themselves. but my perception changed when i went through two to three phases of those downward spirals..which were i don't know caused by what. i realized that once you are down there in your own mind's created darkness, it's really hard to be strong and get up and look after your own self. although that's the only true  solution, but to reach the solution you need a ladder of medication maybe or some sort of talk. 
in this era of money and recognition don't loose yourself to your work ...whatever you become you will attract, so don't just down if you are depressed, talk it out, always have a company that will listen to you. and don't ever be afraid to tell that's the only ladder which could actually get you to sanity and self love 
talk it out .
.
.

text:
i fail all the time.
i try to be a teacher, a role model, a beacon of light to everyone i meet.
of course, i'm young but age is not a measurement of wisdom

i have done things i'm ashamed of.
i have hurt people. i have hurt myself. i feel like i should have died from the power of my own self hatred 
i was alone and hurting. seeking any kind of guidance. i didn't find peace in religion like everyone else seems to find. 
i want to help people realize there's more to life than exams, bills, popularity, and any other sources of stress.

you deserve love. 
self love is what saved me from my darkest thoughts.

i urge you reading this, whoever you are, please to learn to truly love yourself. "darkness cannot drive out darkness, only light can do that. hate cannot drive out hate, only love can do that." love is the most powerful emotion. every living being deserves love. i hope you learn to truly love everything around you. when you do your life will be transformed

learn from past mistakes. that's what this page is for. i hope maybe one day this reaches someone who needs it. my dms are always open to anyone who needs someone to talk to. stay strong and love

#starwars #thelastjedi #yoda #jedi #jedimaster #quotes #mlk #love #selflove #blacklivesmatter  #lgbt #lgbtq #theforceawakens #soloastarwarsstory #metoo

i have hurt people. i have hurt myself. i feel like i should have died from the power of my own self hatred 
i was alone and hurting. seeking any kind of guidance. i didn't find peace in religion like everyone else seems to find. 
i want to help people realize there's more to life than exams, bills, popularity, and any other sources of stress.

you deserve love. 
self love is what saved me from my darkest thoughts.

i urge you reading this, whoever you are, please to learn to truly love yourself. "darkness cannot drive out darkness, only light can do that. hate cannot drive out hate, only love can do that." love is the most powerful emotion. every living being deserves love. i hope you learn to truly love everything around you. when you do your life will be transformed

learn from past mistakes. that's what this page is for. i hope maybe one day this reaches someone who needs it. my dms are always open to anyone who needs someone to talk to. stay strong and love

text:
-- i think it's so bizarre that i've gotten so much push back about my work (the neuropsychology of whiteness) from my creepy as fuck publisher to getting my posts deleted on ig ...even though i don't even have followers like that (really, calm down instagram) when there are *literally articles* with cover art featuring a massive sweep of blond hair *swallowing* perception-oriented facial orifices (eyes, ears, nose...) wild .

i think it's basically because i'm black and my dads rich and my mothers white (that they way i personally identify), and people just want me to be white washed bc it's more comfortable for everyone ...else
.

im keeping a peripheral analog about it as i go forth, bc im just not stopping any time soon. and frankly, it's just not that offensive. what is offensive? the 80% of racists, most of whom pretend not to know
.

and i just fucking love this photo, particularly with the little flower, as if it's a "blind as a fucking bat" cultural hairdo. like, white girl in her 60s walks into a salon like, "i want the 'culturally ignorant for life' style. i have a #metoo gala tonight"
.

and all i actually study at this point is american white people talking to other american white people about the psychology of american white people, so for each pairing? i love one (typically the author) and just study the other
.

white trash meg the food photographer and meg newman are *adjacent* to my work, though i *have* tossed both legal cases around in class bc *what the fuck were either of them thinking?* oh, absolutely nothing beyond their whitness, particularly white trash meg bc we *actually have* visual evidence, eye witnesses and audio, and like, 300 emails... and she committed an actual felony (when she tried to repurpose the narrative and preform an inauthentic innocence) and lied to the *court* ...smh. but this *massive amount* of white girl hysteria is being carefully categorized by me bc anecdotal tails are interesting, but it's professionally inappropriate to factor my own shit in .

im too black for that; it actually fucks up the objectivity necessary to cast the net as wide as it needs to be
.

text:
[please read] today was rough and i am reaching out to this wonderful community for advice. 
coming from an extremely conservative household and family, simply my presence in a space with my conservative family members is tense. fortunately, it only occurs 2x a year, on the holidays. my family is very small, so when tensions run high or conversations get heated, sides are taken quickly and it always ends up being me vs the rest of the people in the room. 
today, my uncle had the audacity to say that women in college are â€œruining menâ€™s livesâ€ by â€œcrying rapeâ€ when they just â€œregretted having sex and werenâ€™t mature enough to handle those emotions.â€ he said that these men were â€œsufferingâ€ because of the women that â€œpointed the fingerâ€ at them and that these menâ€™s lives were â€œruined forever.â€ after this and much more victim blaming, i had to get up and remove myself from the toxic and dangerous space, however, i remained silent. in any other situation i wouldâ€™ve spoken up and welcomed the debate. i would not have rested until he understood why he was wrong. 
as a rape survivor i shouldâ€™ve spoken up. i shouldâ€™ve defended myself and my fellow sisters. iâ€™m angry at myself that i did not. and for what reason? to make sure everyone else in the room wasnâ€™t uncomfortable? itâ€™s bullshit and iâ€™m sick and tired of my family dynamics bullying me into submission. how do you all handle these situations? i need guidance. thank you in advance.

text:
i am practicing self love.

it's taken me a long time to learn to love and accept myself...especially my hair. coming from a mixed background has sometimes made me feel like i dont belong to a specific culture or group.

tonight at yoga, i reflected on the fact that this has really been the year of self love and priority for me. it's both lovely and overwhelming. after years of being in an abusive relationship, i found my joy, confidence and self esteem really plummeted.

but now i'm rebuilding and celebrating me. this is a really monumental phase on the healing journey. i'm happy to be here, and i hope my story will encourage you in your own.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this thanksgiving i sat back to reflect on all the things in my life that iâ€™m thankful for, and how many things i have experienced thus far. .
i have tremendous gratitude for all the universe has blessed me with, for both the struggles and the dark times as well as the abundance.  iâ€™ve learned so much about myself and learned how strong i really am. iâ€™ve had to overcome some really tough things over the past 5 years ... things that i have kept private and suffered in silence. no more . itâ€™s time i speak my truth. iâ€™ve survived a vicious physical attack, one so horrific and demoralizing and many other attacks on me, and my professionalism in my position at work by some really miserable jealous and desperate people, but the point is that i overcame them , stronger then ever before.
i didnâ€™t understand why i had to go through this when i was going through the hardest times in my life, over these past 5 years. the #universe makes no mistakes. i had these experiences because i now understand after lots and lots of work, i needed them to grow in order to become the person i am becoming. i could never speak like this, and of these traumas publicly before. i suffered in silence. after suffering a complete mental breakdown, i fought hard for 2 years to overcome my depression, anxiety and ptsd from these traumas. over the past 2 years, iâ€™ve learned that speaking my truth and showing #vulnerability does not in any way or form mean weakness. it means strength. super human strength. #unfuckwithable strength. .
i courageously walked away from my career and began a new one . i walked away from toxicity, jealousy and everything and everyone that sucked the spirit and soul out of me. i also walked away from the same career that i loved and people that i loved . it was difficult but in the end... i chose me. i had to love myself enough and put myself.. my sanity and my life first.
i now choose to speak about being brutally attacked because if there is one woman out there suffering in shame and in silence, i want to sit beside her and hold her hand. i want  her to know that one day she too will overcome her pain and sheâ€™s not alone and she too has super human strength .

text:
an older picture i took after the second move out. so life has been difficult lately. i'm trying to deal with it but i've been rather silent at least on this side of the instagram. but, i wanted to take a moment and say how i much i appreciate you all. you're all loved. if you ever need to talk, i'm here. you may feel alone sometimes, but honestly, we all do. as humans we liked to give the appearance of having everything together when we are actually struggling and/or feeling incredibly alone. and, this silly notion that we have to get through everything alone on the basis of us being functional-adult humans is what causes so much unnecessary suffering and mental illnesses. it's okay to talk you guys. so if you need to talk (even if you're an unknown stranger here on ig) there's always someone who will listen. even for friends and family, if i can't help or listen, there is someone who can. you just need to be open to finding them and look for them. 
love to you all, 
kaila ğŸ’«

text: i still remember the hopeful energy from the warm air of a summer evening in manhattan. that energy that pushed me out of my comfort zone, encouraged me to meet new people, a risk i rarely take. i still remember the disappointment when i wasnâ€™t seen, and worse, when i finally was acknowledged only to discover i had been forgotten. adult me recoiled into my former preteen self; unworthy, invisible, silenced. i still remember the way the sour in my stomach, that iâ€™ve come to quickly identify as shame, was instantly soothed when charlotte stood up for me, reclaiming my seat at the table just when i had so easily given it up. ğŸ™‹ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ if youâ€™ve ever been made to feel invisible and find yourself constantly battling that inner narrative that tells you, â€˜you donâ€™t deserve to be hereâ€™, remember that you have the agency to stand up for yourself. more importantly, remember that you have the power to speak up for others when you sense that their own shame is keeping them quiet. because it was only when charlotte spoke up for me that i realized i did deserve to be heard, seen and present. the silenced cannot make space for themselves, we must put aside our resentment for the privileges we lack and use the ones we do have to lift each other up. ğŸ’ªğŸ½ so today iâ€™m thankful for new york city; for teaching me that i deserve to be seen and heard, for encouraging me to be assertive, and showing me how to carve space for myself. and iâ€™m thankful for women like @charlottenoelle_ who lead by example.

text: photo by @rosebaca | let us tell you about someone you probably know nothing about â€” but you should. her name is adlene harrison, and she was the first woman to be mayor of dallas. "at age 95, she is as feisty â€” and at times ornery â€” as she was the day she walked into city hall," according to columnist sharon grigsby, who spoke with her recently. a political outsider, harrison served on the city council from 1973 to 1977. she wore her non-establishment label proudly. when asked about the â€œfirstsâ€ attributed to her â€” first female mayor in dallas, first jewish woman to serve as mayor of a major u.s. city â€” she grimaced. â€œi donâ€™t know that that changed my life or anybody elseâ€™s. but it did say to other women, â€˜go out there and run for office and do the best you can.â€™" so is harrison an advocate of the #metoo movement? again, gruff, no-nonsense adlene: â€œi hate to tell you this, but i donâ€™t even think that much about the metoo movement. i just think about movement â€” i donâ€™t care how it comes.â€ harrisonâ€™s experience in politics was different than that of other women who have accused powerful men of misconduct. but the trailblazer now fears too much division between the sexes. â€œiâ€™ve always had a lot of help from men, and iâ€™ll always remember what that help was.â€

text:
this is an original i was recording or more precisely had to write and record although i was having swollen vocal chords. what was such an urgency you ask? then the answer is mental space. i had to put out the chaos by any means.
i am the person who believes that diseases are simply energy defficiency and disorders. specifically i believed that mental disorders arent actually treated by medication rather one has to heal themselves. but my perception changed when i went through two to three phases of those downward spirals..which were i don't know caused by what. i realized that once you are down there in your own mind's created darkness, it's really hard to be strong and get up and look after your own self. although that is the only true  solution, but to reach the solution you need a ladder of medication maybe or some sort of talk. 
in this era of money and recognition don't loose yourself to your work or society or some situation...whatever you become is what you will attract, so don't just sit down and drag your life if you are depressed, talk it out, always have a company that will listen to you, i will listen if there is no body whom you could talk to. and don't ever be afraid to tell that's the only ladder which could actually get you to sanity and self love 
talk it out .
.
.

text:
happy white ribbon day. â£â£
â£a thirty-year-old victorian woman has been shot and killed by her boyfriend. â£â£
â£her name was emily miller. â£â£
she leaves behind four children under ten. â£
her death brings the tally of women murdered by men this year to 61. â£â£
of this number, 41 women were murdered by a male intimate partner. â£
[ we apologise for the binary gender expression of this data, it is not acceptable to erase trans and enby folk, but currently police do not represent victims more accurately. ]â£â£
when will these numbers alarm australians?â£â£â£
when will the statistics hit home?â£â£
when will we realise we arenâ€™t doing enough?â£â£
thank you to @impactforwomen for keeping up-to-date records of this heartbreaking data. â£â£
you can find the tally here:â£â£
http://www.impactforwomen.org.au/death-toll-of-violence-in-australia-2018.htmlâ£â£

text:
for many people, art is not only for self-expression, but also a powerful tool to speak up about the pressing issues in our society, namely violence against gender and sexuality.

it is an issue we are all familiar with, yet we don't talk about enough. we tend to shy away when we talk about violence, be it when it comes to ourselves or other people who experienced it. this coming #16daysofactivism, we hope to open a safe space to tell stories, engage in conversations, and become part of a better change.

i am humbled to be a part of @enambelasffest in telling a story about una, a survivor of abuse as a child, and her confrontation with her abuser in #jpacblackbird.

come along and enjoy the stories in the festival and #hearmetoo at #enambelasffest!

text:
when i was four,
my pants were pulled down,
and my uncle pushed himself in, behind closed doors.
i didn't say anything.
i knew no one would believe. 
when i was eight,
my neighbour made me touch her parts
promising me the chocolate she kept as bait. 
i didn't say anything. 
i knew no one would believe me. ............................ we often find these words to have a female voice. but lately many men have openly voiced the same. and it is time we hear them out!
watch #hijabininja 's new video.

text: happy gratitoodle. been thinking far too much,...obviously. finally starting to feel better, not complaining just being honest, my ptsd has semi calmed down and i feel like i'm not tripping balls in interactions with others for the first time in 14 months, still alright with all the drive that happened. happy to have reached this point stayed true to myself and accomplished an over a decade long mission. been thinking about the kids in cages, it's painful to reflect on. i turned out ok, though to be honest those kids definetly no matter long they sit. not saying i'm giving up but the damage to them has already gone too far. whether they be released yesterday, or tomorrow, they're gonna be the ones society never accepts, no matter how hard they try, how nice, how tolerant, how smart, how helpful, if they survive without being offed or offing themselves due to inability to relate. being raised on love is different than being raised to survive. i'm happy for the friends i do know, the people i meet that are committing a radical act being themselves in a world where so many aren't. it's an honor to be exposed to any, so few, of genuine humanness, those are the people to fight for, to live for. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #grateful #thankstonotthemanyjustthefew

text:
i just want it to be known that this is the exact outfit i was wearing this morning when some random man twice my age decided to go out of his way and make innapropriate sexual comments about my appearance. 
iâ€™m not normally one for posting things of this nature on social media, but honestly if i donâ€™t use the voice i have to call out scary and disgusting acts, it just lets this sort of behaviour happen again and again. 
i was sitting in my car on the way to the office when some man in the car next to me kept rolling down his window at the lights acting like he had to tell me something. after 3 sets of lights, i finally wound my window down to see if maybe there was something wrong only to be told â€œiâ€™m sorry but you caught my attention, i cannot stop looking at your thighs in those tightsâ€. on what planet does any female just trying to make their way to work ask for these sorts of comments?! after rolling my window back up in horror, the man proceeded to start yelling abuse at me and then changed lanes behind my car as i was driving. i thought he was going to follow me to work, it was terrifying. 
this is not okay and i cannot believe that i felt embarrassed about what i was wearing as a result of his comments. 
every day sexual harassment is a thing. sometimes itâ€™s more subtle with slight sexual innuendos. but other times itâ€™s overt and aggressive and absolutely terrifying. 
i deserve to feel safe driving to work in my own car in the morning and not feel like i should be driving with my doors locked at all times.
so often when moments like this occur, weâ€™re made to feel like this is our fault and they we did something to bring on this sort of attention. i just want to say that any woman sitting in her car, listening to a podcast and just trying to get to work does not ever want this sort of attention. itâ€™s not flattering, itâ€™s scary and it needs to end.
#metoo #metoomovement

text: every year i volunteer at schoolies week and every year i am increasingly impressed by how awesome todayâ€™s young people are. high school, and adolescence, has always been tough but now throw in increasing academic pressures, social media, rising depression and anxiety, rising stis, #metoo, and a whole bunch more. these young people absolutely deserve the opportunity to let their hair down and our job as adults it to support them to minimise harm. people often ask me why i volunteer each year and the answer is simple, there are people who sit at home and complain about the youth of today and people who get out there and get the amazing opportunity of seeing just how fantastic the youth of today are. #sexologist #hope #future #party #allyoungonce #youth #goldcoast

gratitude makes everything grow ğŸŒ» there is so much i am grateful for - a god who loves me unconditionally, my incredible husband, a family who cares about me, my 7 nieces and nephews, a church who is on fire for christ, my crossfit community/family and the ability to exercise my body, an amazing job where i can work from anywhere with my husband, the ability to to do what i love - studying to become a dietitian, my beneath the surface family and all your encouragement to keep going. iâ€™m thankful for the simple things also - like nathan jokingly getting down on one knee yesterday handing me my favorite cup of coffee. or getting to take an hour walk this beautiful morning to pray & reflect, and taking another hour walk with my nieces & nephews. simple. beautiful. moments.  the moments that go unnoticed. but most of all - today i am giving thanks for the hard times. because the hard times are what we are usually never grateful for. itâ€™s easy to be grateful for good things, but to actually be grateful for hard times? thatâ€™s where true faith comes in. so you want to know how to truly be thankful? give thanks for those hard things! 
james 1:2 says â€œdear brothers and sisters, when troubles come your way, consider it an opportunity for great joy.â€ true joy isnâ€™t the opposite of trouble, itâ€™s a choice you can have despite your trouble.
you can choose joy in the middle of a brokenness, painful memories, or even failing health.
through the power of the holy spirit, troubles might actually be your bridge to true thankfulness and happiness ğŸ’œ

text:
yes that's us!! one of those crazy families that treats our pet as a hooman. but this cat isn't just any cat she is a huge part of family, and came into our life just at the right time, and i think we needed her just as much as she needed us. for 3 months she didn't want to go outside she was happy and content chilling with us inside. she has the most incredible instinct and is always there when we are sick, hurt or just not quite ourselves. there is so much love for this precious wee gem, and she has been a huge blessing for tara as well. despite the "presents" she has brought to me recently, i thought it was something cool to do with tara to show her that we should show love, kindness, and celebrate rusty for the special wee thing she is, yes she probably thinks we are mad, i don't care.

text:
âŒ #metoo âŒ â€¢
do you know what i wish we didn't have to normalise?
talking about sexual abuse.
opening up about the trauma it causes, the deep roots it grows into abuse survivors and their generational lines, and the inseparable histories it shares with related mental health issues.
â€¢
i've grappled for a long time about sharing my story. 
fear has held me back for so many reasons, some perhaps obvious and others i hadn't really anticipated but encountered whilst writing this post;
- what if no one believes me?
- who would care about something that happened over 10 years ago?
- how will people look at me now they know? will i seem like lesser of a person to them?
- what will my close friends and family who didn't know think?
â€¢
trust me, i've probably thought about this more than anything in my life.
my past follows me everywhere;
- it is with me as i lie in bed at night,
- or when i walk down an empty alleyway,
- it is with me as i work,
- and it's sometimes with me as i am wrapped in a lovers embrace
â€¢
so it's weird not to talk about this silent intruder that embedded itself in my family's tree, that became a part of me.
â€¢
- 1 in 6 girls, and 1 in 9 boys below the age of 15 have experienced sexual assault
- 1 in 6 women, and 1 in 20 men since the age of 15 have experienced sexual assault
â€¢
that is around an estimated 4.6 million people within australia (that have reported their abuse), or close to 20% of the population who have been affected by this taboo, detrimental and psychologically damaging event. â€¢
this isn't an isolated issue, it doesn't limit itself to a particular demographic, socio-economic or age group. it can affect anyone. even that bright, bubbly girl who is smiling in the picture above ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸
â€¢
i am an active supporter of the white ribbon organisation within australia, and stand for the oaths listed here: https://www.whiteribbon.org.au/stop-violence-against-women/supporter/ . become a supporter. open the conversation. stop the cycle. â€¢
statistics: australian institute of health and welfare (2018), family, domestic and sexual violence in australia 2018, www.aihw.gov.au
â€¢
support materials: 
https://au.reachout.com/ 
https://www.whiteribbon.org.au/

text:
have you listened to/watched fr. #stendlrast on @ted ? today is a great day for it, but so is tomorrow or any other day. i had the pleasure of being close to him at @wisdom2conf a few years back, and he has an undeniable presence radiating from him, or practicing moment-to-moment #gratitude. sound like #mindfulness? yeah kind of, and a good entry point to #christians as he is a monk. 
two quotes to whet your appetite:
â€œwhat is the connection between happiness and gratefulness? many people would say, well, that's very easy. when you are happy, you are grateful. but think again. is it really the happy people that are grateful? we all know quite a number of people who have everything that it would take to be happy, and they are not happy, because they want something else or they want more of the same. and we all know people who have lots of misfortune, misfortune that we ourselves would not want to have, and they are deeply happy. they radiate happiness. you are surprised. why? because they are grateful. so it is not happiness that makes us grateful. it's gratefulness that makes us happy. if you think it's happiness that makes you grateful, think again. it's gratefulness that makes you happy.â€ â€œbut once in a while, something very difficult is given to us, and when this difficult thing occurs to us, it's a challenge to rise to that opportunity, and we can rise to it by learning something which is sometimes painful. learning patience, for instance. we have been told that the road to peace is not a sprint, but is more like a marathon. that takes patience. that's difficult. it may be to stand up for your opinion, to stand up for your conviction. that's an opportunity that is given to us. to learn, to suffer, to stand up, all these opportunities are given to us, but they are opportunities, and those who avail themselves of those opportunities are the ones that we admire. they make something out of life. and those who fail get another opportunity. we always get another opportunity. that's the wonderful richness of life.â€ #happythanksgiving

text:
had the best thanksgiving brunch @barbacoa_boise !

i have been doing this bone broth cleanse that was amazing but was so excited to eat! 
this was one of the best buffets i have been to and i have been to literally a ton of them all over the world because i love buffets so much! i wish i had taken more pics of the various buffets i have been fortunate to eat at. 
there were so many options, traditional thanksgiving food, fresh seafood like oysters and shrimp, lobster ravioli, various empanada and flat breads, pulled pork, prime rib, soups, salads, and so many desserts! 
last night i was a bit lonely as can happen during the holidays when we are bombarded with advertising about how holidays should look and wished i had a family of my own and a big house with lots of cooking planned, etc.  in the past these feelings of inadequacy led me to escape with alcohol and ruin my holidays by poisoning my mind body and spirit. 
last night i did some foam rolling and took a bath and went to bed and my feelings of loneliness were replaced with gratitude for the freedom my life provides and the ability to enjoy such a wonderful experience today with my parents. i went to yoga and enjoyed the community and practice and know my happiness does not come from a hallmark holiday. 
sometimes these thoughts and lonely feelings are just randomly there, they leave just as fast as they come and we don't have to act on them. we can just pause, go to bed and wake up sober and thankful. ğŸ™
comparison is the theif of joy. the mind always wants to compare but it's not necessary, we can all enjoy a beautiful holiday season regardless of our relationship status ğŸ’›

text:
grateful for the lessons i learned in israel/ palestine: 
1-  compassionate activism: it is important to host different perspectives and not lose sight of the humanity of the people we vehemently disagree with. they all have a reason why they see the world the way they do. only from that can the most powerful form of and resistance emerge. our activism should come from a courageous heart full of love, not just our anger and fear.
2-  patience: â€œthe arc of the moral universe is long, but it bends toward justice.â€ mlk. i know that the work i, and others, are engaged in is meaningful and necessary because it sets the ground for changes that are yet to come, even if i wonâ€™t get to see them. knowing it gives me hope and imbues my work with meaning.
3-  inevitability of pain: i used to be filled with so many â€œwhat ifs:â€ what if we never occupied those damn territories, what it the settlement project never existed, what if extremism never emerged. itâ€™s pointless. and only serves to hang the blame on one side. history is a winding road i need to honor, even when it hurts. we donâ€™t know the trajectory of events that ultimately swings back towards social change. for example, this american president is incredibly damaging on all fronts. and at the same time, he was an amplifier for social movements like #metoo (would it have erupted like that without him?) and powerful political awakening in this country. our pain is a catalyst for change. could change ever happen without it?
4-  no binaries: truth is plural. the only way to be right it to let go of being right. practice discernment, vulnerability, and question everything â€“ especially your own beliefs. when you do that, you enter a conversational space with the universe that is truly miraculous, where possibilities for change are real. 
5-  please remember, between the trenches there are incredible people â€“ teachers, healers, thinkers, mediators engaged in truly transformational work. we donâ€™t hear about them. we donâ€™t see them in the news. but there are there, resilient, creative, working against all odds. for all of them, i am truly grateful.

text: gabrielle union as julia rossmore in daddy's little girls (2007) | in this 200th post in the #herstaircasescene series gabrielle union celebrated. union has long been an outspoken feminist voice in hollywood, precursing many of the celebrity women that have started speaking out only fairly recently. among others, union has been a big supporter of planned parenthood for years now, as well as an active contributor to debates regarding mysogny, toxic masculinity, and rape culture. in her memoirs - we're going to need more wine - she also bravely shared the story of being raped herself. after the #metoo movement hit full steam, gabrielle also specfically asked to look beyond the high-profile stories of primarily white stars, to consider the experiences of all women. she is a hero of intersectional feminism.

text:
aut viam inveniam aut faciam - i will either find a way or make one. 
this time last year i was embarking on a  journey to have one of the best nights of my life. a night involving wrestling,  friends, subway, and giving lots of ... thanks. not knowing that night only set in motions series of a events that would dismantle my entire life. 
don't let love keep you in pain. don't let pain make you hard. find a way out. and if you can't find a way, make one. 
i'm so thankful i made my own way out. i'm so thankful for the people who have supported. who have believed. who have loved. who have cared. i would not have made it through this last year without you. 
#thanksgiving
#metoo
#fme

text:
iâ€™m not one to talk about my past because i donâ€™t want it to define me. i donâ€™t want to be defined by what iâ€™ve survived and what iâ€™ve endured. with that being said, itâ€™s thanksgiving and i feel like should share on this one. the only way for me to express how thankful i am for these last few years it to open up about my past. i donâ€™t like to celebrate holidays like this. every time i see a post on facebook about happy memories and happy childhoods i just feel sad. i feel sad because my childhood was filled with the lies and abuse of a man who let booze control his mind and his life and a woman who let him do what ever he wanted. the person in my life who was supposed to protect me and love me failed me in every possible way. on april 20, 2016 my mother and stepfather were arrested and everything changed. i am so thankful for everyone who was there that day. iâ€™m thankful for the police and the detectives who worked my case and who believed when it felt like no one could believe such a horrible claim. iâ€™m thankful for every cps worker, every social worker, every single person who has been with me these last two years. iâ€™m thankful for everyone who has come in to my life, i can even express how thankful i am to all my friends for unknowingly showing me the world wasnâ€™t completely horrible and could be full of such amazing and colorful people. for my family who stayed by my side and for holding my hand as my mother and stepfather were given 40 to life for their crimes. for holding me while i cried and laughing with me. iâ€™m so thankful that i survived and that iâ€™m still surviving. iâ€™m thankful that iâ€™m alive, and the the first time in many years, wanting to continue to live. i am so thankful for the last few years and iâ€™m looking forward to everything thatâ€™s yet to comeâ¤ï¸ i am not a victim, i wonâ€™t let them take my name like that. i am a survivor and i am so unbelievably thankful for that.
.

.
.
